Important paragraph:
“Now, there are some important caveats to this result. First of all, it’s just one paper -- most minimum-wage studies don’t look at the number of hours that employees work, since this data tends to be hard to come by. As a result, there are lots of studies about how minimum wage affects job numbers, but relatively few on how it affects hours.

Because the new Seattle Minimum Wage Study paper is just one paper, many people will inevitably question whether it used the right measurement techniques. Ben Zipperer and John Schmitt of the Economic Policy Institute have already written about a number of potential issues with the University of Washington researchers’ choice of methods. It’s possible that the study’s authors chose the wrong set of cities to compare to, or underestimated the number of workers who moved into higher-wage positions as a result of the policy change. They also didn’t measure chain restaurants, which constitute a large chunk of the industry. Until many more such studies are done, there will be a lot of uncertainty about whether minimum wage causes employers to cut working hours.

But despite these caveats and uncertainties, the University of Washington paper should give pause to the activists and politicians who want a nationwide $15 minimum wage.”

Interesting article which discusses using observational data to make conclusions: <https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2017-06-27/a-sign-to-go-slow-on-the-15-minimum-wage> not a bad job since their only goal was to give pause and lead to more discussion in the future

Hi folks!  Thanks for coming to the talk!  Ben said that he’d really appreciate feedback and/or questions on the talk, so please send those to me (Slack DM) and I’ll collate and send on to him (anonymous if you like, or include your email and I’ll note which questions came from whom).  Also stay tuned for a future talk more focused on hiring/Facebook :slightly_smiling_face:

<!channel> *Talk Starting in the Theater in a few minutes!*

*Who: Ben Devienne,* Head of Data Science at Gameloft until the end of June and soon-to-be *Head of Analytics at Facebook.*

*About:* Ben has given over 20 international conferences in the past 5 years, including a TEDx talk. He is a peer reviewer for a data science journal, and has been a permanent lecturer in 2 universities since 2013. He has been credited in 22 video games.

*What:* “Introduction to Video Game Data Science”

*Topics covered*:

- What does the supermarket industry and free mobile games have in common?
- How to deal with ridiculously unbalanced data sets and whales
- Predicting revenue 2 years ahead with only a few hours of data
- How graph theory and stratified recommendation systems change game design
- Hacking players’ DNA: Uneven sequential events analysis 
- The importance of teaching machines what’s a rainy Thursday

*When:* Next Wednesday, June 21st, from 4 - 5 pm.

*Location:* At Galvanize, Theater (in the basement)
